https://www.youtube.com/user/RALLIcampaign</gtr:description><gtr:id>AE1E3F41-5C34-4955-9B6D-C7C0402925DA</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>56b36218d29059.97115111</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Education,Healthcare,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>This fellowship had a number of objectives. Here, a selected and brief summary of some of the key project findings are provided. 



The motivation for the data analyses projects came from the hypothesis that individuals with SLI have an increased risk of autism spectrum disorders (ASD). 



The natural history of SLI is poorly understood, especially in terms of distinctive developmental and psychosocial elements associated with SLI versus those which associated with what may (arguably) be co-morbid conditions such as ASD (SLI+ASD). 

We found evidence of distinctive patterns of early language development in individuals with SLI versus those with ASD. 



The developmental pattern in SLI is characterised by language delay with no evidence of language regression.

 

 This was distinctive from that of individuals with ASD where language loss occurred (Pickles et al., 2009). 



We also found commonalities across SLI and ASD. We found similar levels of social and stereotyped behaviour deficits in the relatives of SLI+ASD and ASD probands (but not in the relatives of SLI only probands). 



There was also a higher rate of ASD (4.3 per cent) in the siblings of SLI probands than would be expected from the general population (Pickles et al., 2013).



In terms of psychosocial adjustment, we found distinctive developmental patterns from childhood to adolescence for social difficulties as compared to behavioural and emotional difficulties. We observed a decrease in behavioural problems from childhood to adolescence. 



Emotional problems were still evident in adolescence. Importantly there was a higher risk of increased social difficulties in SLI, with friendships being particularly problematic for individuals with SLI+ASD. Both subgroups were equally vulnerable to anxiety and depression symptoms (Durkin &amp;amp; Conti-Ramsden, 2010; Durkin et al., 2012; St. Clair et al., 2011; Wadman et al., 2008; 2011 ).



For educational achievement, in particular reading/literacy skills, individuals with SLI+ASD had better reading accuracy skills than individuals with SLI only. This pattern was evident from childhood to adolescence. Of particular importance was the identification of a significant gap between what individuals with SLI+ASD could read and what they could understand when reading (St. Clair et al., 2010). 



We also found that literacy skills were a key factor in adolescents with SLI use of new technology (Durkin et al.,2011 ; Conti-Ramsden et al., 2012). In terms of education in preparation for employment, individuals with SLI+ASD were significantly less likely to engage in work experience activities (eg having a part-time job) during secondary schooling than those with SLI only (Durkin et al., 2011).



Developmental patterns of language and non-verbal skills from childhood to adolescence were also examined in detail on children with SLI as a whole. 



We found evidence of stable growth from childhood to adolescence but only in verbal skills. Different developmental trajectories were found for nonverbal skills. 



Importantly, we found evidence of slowing down of growth of nonverbal skills in a third of children with SLI in middle childhood and adolescence (Conti-Ramsden et al. 2012).</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Enhancing quality of life of individuals with SLI and their parents. Our work has provided a voice for young people with SLI and their parents by publishing their views (Simkin &amp;amp; Conti-Ramsden, 2009) and involving them in the research process (focus groups with a) young people and b) parents).



Increasing professionals' and parents' knowledge of the longer term consequences of SLI. We have provided practitioner reviews (Durkin &amp;amp; Conti-Ramsden, 2010) and chapters that summarise information (Conti-Ramsden, 2008; Conti-Ramsden &amp;amp; Durkin, 2011) as well as accessible publications (Conti-Ramsden, 2009 CLTT commentary; Wadman et al., 2009 Bulletin RCSLT; Conti-Ramsden &amp;amp; Durkin, 2010, article in Afasic News magazine). We have also undertaken seminars and workshops for these users of research in the UK (Nov 2008, June 2009, Sept. 2009; Nov 2009).



Raising awareness of SLI internationally. We have published a summary of some of our key findings in French (Conti-Ramsden &amp;amp; Durkin, 2010). We have also undertaken a series of activities in Spanish speaking countries (Spain and Latin America) including a series of workshops in Spain (2008), Argentina (2010) and Chile (2010) and a series of media articles published in Latin America (2010). We have also undertaken a series of dissemination activities in Australia (2011).



Providing evidence for an intervention programme. The Narrative Intervention Programme (2011, Speechmark) by Dr. Victoria Joffe is designed for secondary school pupils and uses evidence from our key research findings to form the basis for the development of the programme, including its rationale and foundations.





Our work on the developmental trajectories of skills of individuals with SLI is likely to impact future policy and practice related to services needed for older children and adolescents/young people. There has been substantial emphasis on SLI as a childhood disorder and on early intervention (both important and necessary). Our work is providing evidence of persistence of difficulties and particular areas of vulnerability and risk in SLI in middle childhood and adolescence.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>9F5D3B08-BDF1-425A-A044-ADA99042D6B5</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>r-4592468705.580075b2f016c8</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Other</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>F8F33E3A-AD8A-434A-957F-F5CE5B547DEB</gtr:id><gtr:title>Growth of reading skills in children with a history of specific language impairment: the role of autistic symptomatology and language-related abilities.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>The British journal of developmental psychology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/a5cf0e1d7931161bda3ead0dcbbd72a0"><gtr:id>a5cf0e1d7931161bda3ead0dcbbd72a0</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>St Clair MC</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0261-510X</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>pm_53cbfbbbfbbb050c1</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>D63A34D7-D79D-4BF7-B1BA-81112A938842</gtr:id><gtr:title>Young people with specific language impairment: A review of social and emotional functioning in adolescence</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Child Language Teaching and Therapy</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/855fa7defdb1414c584bd